<chapter><title> PROTEUS Newton's Method Reading Questions </title>

    <!-- After the Introduction (motivation vs. bisection) -->
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-why-needed">
    <title>Why Newton's Method?</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Why do we need approximation methods like Newton’s Method instead of algebraic solutions for equations such as <m>x^5+x+1=0</m>?
        </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Because the algebra is too messy but still possible with enough effort.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>No—some equations cannot be solved in closed form with standard functions, not just because of messy algebra.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Because many equations have no algebraic solution in terms of familiar functions.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Exactly—Newton’s Method provides approximate solutions when algebraic ones don’t exist.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Because computers are unable to handle exact solutions.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not true—computers can handle exact symbolic work in some cases, but the limitation lies in mathematics itself.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
    </choices>
    </exercise>


